%N A397392 A knight starts at the origin on an infinite chessboard. In each step, it makes a knight's move to the unvisited point in the slit plane (without touching or crossing the negative y-axis) that is closest to the origin, avoiding steps that inevitably lead to a dead end at some point in the future. See comments for how ties are resolved. a(n) is the x-coordinate of the knight after the n-th step.
%C A397392 The line segment between two consecutive positions is not permitted to intersect the negative y-axis.
%C A397392 Ties are resolved by minimizing lengths of 2nd differences, 3rd differences, and so on (see A396936). If there is still a tie after comparing the n-th differences, the lexicographically largest point is chosen. This last rule seems never to come into play, except for the very first step.
%C A397392 Backtracking (discarding a candidate move because it inevitably leads to a dead end) is needed for the first time in the 431st step, in which the step to (-1,-10) is discarded because all its neighbors are already visited. Instead the knight moves to (-4,13). (-1,-10) is also the position closest to the origin of the positions that are never visited. Among the first 1000000 steps, backtracking is needed 114 times. The majority of the discarded steps are steps to boundary points (points with |x|==1 and y<0).
%C A397392 The first time the 3rd differences need to be compared is at the 47056th step. Among the first 1000000 steps, differences of order higher than 3 never need to be compared; 3rd differences are needed 10 times.
